    Circadian Time Prediction Using tauFisher

    Michelle N. Ngo

    Last compiled: November 22, 2021

    Introduction.Rmd

    Set-up

    Load the package.

    library(tauFisher)
library(dplyr)
#> 
#> Attaching package: 'dplyr'
#> The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
#> 
#>     filter, lag
#> The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
#> 
#>     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
set.seed(123)

    Import data

    For this tutorial, we will predict the circadian time of suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) transcriptomic samples from C57BL/6J mice. These mice were fed normal chow through an entire circadian cycle (24 hours) and samples were collected every four hours. A total of six time points with three replicates each (18 samples) were sequenced on the Illumina HiSeq 4000.

    For more details, see Tognini P et al. (2020). The data set can be downloaded from the GEO database: accession number GSE157077.

    tauFisher requires:

    1. A matrix of gene expression data with rows as genes and columns as samples.
    2. A vector of the circadian time for each sample.
    datafile <- system.file("extdata", "GSE157077_mouse_scn_control.tsv", 
                    package = "tauFisher", mustWork = TRUE)
data <- utils::read.delim(file = datafile, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
print(dim(data))
#> [1] 24883    19

    Pre-process data

    All genes in the data matrix should be unique; if they are not, we will take their average expression.

    # Take the average expression if there are non-unique genes
df <- data[stats::complete.cases(data[,-1]), ] %>%
  dplyr::mutate(ID = toupper(ID)) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(ID) %>%
  dplyr::summarise_all(mean)  %>%
  as.data.frame()

# Set the rownames to be the genes and remove the ID column 
rownames(df) <- df$ID
df <- df[,-1]

    For this data set, the column names are the sample times and replicate indicator. We will parse the column names to obtain a vector of time points.

    time <- as.numeric(vapply(stringr::str_split(colnames(df), "_"),
                          '[', 2, FUN.VALUE = character(1)) )
replicate <- as.numeric(vapply(stringr::str_split(colnames(df), "_"),
                          '[', 4, FUN.VALUE = character(1)) )

    tauFisher

    We will train tauFisher on the first two replicates and test on the third.

    # Set training index
train_idx <- which(replicate != 3)

# Subset train data
train_df <- df[, train_idx]
train_time <- time[train_idx]

# Subset test data
test_df <- df[, -train_idx] 
test_time <- time[-train_idx]

    Find the periodic genes

    Since we are testing on the third replicates, there are no missing time points.

    Note that if there are missing time points, JTK_Cycle requires the data set to have a column of NAs for each missing point. The columns are also assumed to be in order of time, for example: CT0_REP1, CT0_REP2, CT4_REP1, CT4_REP2, ....

    For more details, please see the documentation for the meta2d function in MetaCycle or the JTK_Cycle package.

    We will use both Lomb-Scargle and JTK_Cycle to find the periodic genes. meta2d will produce a text file (location and name given by parameter out_file) and a folder (location and name given by parameter out_dir) with the results.

    run_metacycle(df=train_df, timepoints=train_time, 
              out_file="inst/extdata/GSE157077_train.txt", 
              out_dir="inst/extdata/GSE157077_meta2d", 
              method=c("JTK", "LS") )
    # Set adjusted p-value threshold to 0.051
genes = find_periodic_genes(input_file="../inst/extdata/GSE157077_meta2d/meta2d_GSE157077_train.txt",
                            test_genes=rownames(test_df),
                            per_method=c("LS", "JTK"),
                            thres=0.051)

print(genes)
#> $LS
#> character(0)
#> 
#> $JTK
#>  [1] "D17ERTD648E" "H1F0"        "NR1D1"       "R74862"      "ABHD17B"    
#>  [6] "ACER3"       "DBP"         "EIF1AD"      "EIF2A"       "FAM83H"     
#> [11] "KCTD12"      "MOB1A"       "RBM3"        "TMEM117"     "USP53"      
#> [16] "NR1D2"

    Train tauFisher

    Since Lomb-Scargle did not produce any significant periodic genes at the 0.05 level, we will proceed with the periodic genes identified by JTK_Cycle.

    trained_JTK <- train_tauFisher(periodic_genes=genes$JTK,
                              train_df=train_df,
                              train_time=train_time,
                              nrep=2,
                              seednum=12345)

    The trained model will output a list with three items:

    1. The genes used for circadian time prediction.

      trained_JTK$Genes
#>  [1] "ABHD17B"     "ACER3"       "D17ERTD648E" "DBP"         "EIF1AD"     
#>  [6] "EIF2A"       "FAM83H"      "H1F0"        "KCTD12"      "MOB1A"      
#> [11] "NR1D1"       "NR1D2"       "R74862"      "RBM3"        "TMEM117"    
#> [16] "USP53"

    2. The PCA embedding.

    3. The trained model.

    Predict circadian time 

    result_JTK <- test_tauFisher(chosen_genes=trained_JTK$Genes,
                             test_df=test_df,
                             test_time=test_time,
                             pca_embedding=trained_JTK$PCA_embedding,
                             trained_model=trained_JTK$Model)

    Evalulate predictions

    The prediction is labeled correct if the predicted time is within 2 hours of the true time.

    calc_error(result_JTK$truth, result_JTK$predicted)
#> $differences
#>   truth pred differences
#> 1     0   20           4
#> 2     4    7          -3
#> 3     8   10          -2
